thumbnail_height":333},{"id":"img_3","url":"https://cdn-tp6.mozu.com/24645-37138/cms/37138/files/a4624bf1-f9f7-47a4-9c68-32803a1e1581?max=250&quality=80&_mzcb=_1781580061268","thumbnail_url":"https://imgs.search.brave.com/1fPA7wzQ1QciY1V0YevYAkMrtWK6GkuqJRLV3ELA8Xg/rs:fit:500:0:1:0/g:ce/aHR0cHM6Ly9jZG4t/dHA2Lm1venUuY29t/LzI0NjQ1LTM3MTM4/L2Ntcy8zNzEzOC9m/aWxlcy9hNDYyNGJm/MS1mOWY3LTQ3YTQt/OWM2OC0zMjgwM2Ex/ZTE1ODE_bWF4PTI1/MCZxdWFsaXR5PTgw/Jl9temNiPV8xNzgx/NTgwMDYxMjY4","title":"Irwin 4 in. Steel Workshop Bench Vise Swivel Base","source":"acehardware.com","page_url":"https://www.acehardware.com/departments/tools/hand-tools/vises","width":250,"height":250,"thumbnail_width":250,"thumbnail_height":250}],"uuid":"4303b826-7277-4a8c-b382-afb64327e880","is_expired":false}],"is_error":false},{"start_timestamp":"2026-06-20T05:55:17.510081Z","stop_timestamp":"2026-06-20T05:55:25.058098Z","type":"text","text":"## How It Works\nA vise has two **jaws** — one fixed and one movable. Turning a **screw handle** (or lever) moves the jaws closer or farther apart, clamping the workpiece with significant force.\n\n## Common Types\n\n- **Bench Vise** — bolted to a workbench; the most common type, used in woodworking and metalworking\n- **Woodworking Vise** — has smooth or wooden jaws to avoid damaging softer materials\n- **Machinist's Vise** — heavy-duty, made for metal; often has a swivel base for angled work\n- **Pipe Vise** — specially designed to grip round pipes without them rolling or slipping\n- **Hand Vise** — a small, handheld version for holding tiny objects like jewelry or electronics\n- **Drill Press Vise** — clamps workpieces to a drill press table for precise drilling\n\n## Key Parts\n- **Fixed jaw** — stationary side, bolted to the base\n- **Movable jaw** — slides in and out via the screw\n- **Screw & handle** — the mechanism that drives clamping force\n- **Anvil** (on some vises) — a flat surface on the back for light hammering\n- **Swivel base** — allows the whole vise to rotate for angled work\n\n## What They're Used For\n- Holding wood while **sawing, chiseling, or planing**\n- Gripping metal while **filing, cutting, or welding**\n- Holding pipes while **threading or cutting**\n- Keeping small parts steady during **assembly or repair**\n\n## Fun Fact\nA good bench vise can exert **thousands of kilograms of clamping force**, making it far more powerful than any human grip.\n\nWould you like to know about a specific type of vise or how to choose one?","citations":[]}],"sender":"assistant","index":5,"created_at":"2026-06-20T05:55:25.083288Z","updated_at":"2026-06-20T05:55:25.083288Z","truncated":false,"stop_reason":"end_turn","attachments":[],"files":[],"sync_sources":[],"parent_message_uuid":"019ee398-f533-7f50-aa07-783c969af952"}]}